Text: This week after a group discussion we set up a Slack channel with Eric so that the whole group can pitch questions to them when they come up with them rather than constant emailing.
This is also convenient for Eric as he uses Slack for his company as well.
We had another meeting with Eric to discuss progress and get further feedback on which data we should be including and displaying.
During this meeting Eric also suggested implementing a user registration/login system.
His idea is to show the basic MSHA data to non-registered users and more detailed state information to registered users.

This isn't too much work to implement but if Eric wants to keep adding more requirements into the project we will have to start turning some of them down as they are outside of the scope and we won't have time to do them.

I decided to put the server work on the back-burner for now and set up a local server using XAMPP so that I can start playing around and testing PHP&MySQL since it is so much easier and less confusing to set up, and free.

I spent most of this week working through PHP tutorials, refreshing my skills and learning how to create a login system and display different content based on being logged in or not per Erics request.
It was nice to refresh my PHP skills but I also forgot how frustrating it can be, especially the debugging process.
But I was able to produce a nice looking banner with a login and signup form inside of a modal, which is connected to a local MySQL database with just a user table in it.
It was interesting to learn about password hashing which has changed since I last remember doing it.
I believe while in polytech I was taught to use SHA256 or MD5.
It seems the standard is to now use bcrypt which incorporates a salt into the password to increase difficulty in breaking into the account.
After I had this working I spent time looking into jQuery and AJAX functions to stop the screen refreshing after form submission and to help give the users better feedback while filling out the form.
This turned out to much harder than I had originally thought but was a good learning experience.

Most of the difficulty from this was just my own mistakes in writing the code, so to stop this happening in future I'll need to pay more attention to the tutorials and it might help to plan the functions and how everything fits together on paper before getting working on it as there are so many different connecting parts in different locations.
As for our group communications, I feel that they could be better.
We spend a lot of time discussing different problems, aspects and ideas for the project but I'm finding it hard to follow or know what my other group members are actually working on.

I'll try to rectify this in our next group meeting and ask what everyone is currently working on and draw up a map of what we have and what we're aiming for, and possibly try to encourage some pair programming.
With the login system done next week Kuku and I will work together to add a map onto this.

Roro is working on the database and is current able to do API calls but not with the MSHA data yet but this shouldn't be far off so then we'll be able to start getting the data to the map and displaying it.
Roro has decided to work using MongoDB which isn't what Kuku wanted so I may have to check if this will work for him before it goes too far.
It would be useful though as Roro has said it has geolocation function for measuring distances which would be perfect for finding locations close to the user location.

Eric also added another new requirement for the map just recently which is that it needs to be satellite view which I'll need to research into but most mapping APIs other than Google don't provide this function.
I want to spend some time next week joining the work we have been doing together as we currently all have little pieces of what will be the whole.
Once it's joined this will hopefully help the group visualize our current progress better as well.
Overall
